column2: review_text

CaliBamboo is a premium bamboo flooring producer.  As the bamboo flooring market collapses, they have been branching out into other areas of flooring.  Be aware that the CaliBamboo product at Lowe's/Home Depot/etc is NOT the same high quality as their signature brand found only at flooring retailers.
How can that happen? It happened because quartz never should have been used in that application. I think your best option is what Fori said and use  stainless over it.

I love this and did something like it in my house with a similar 12" space. It's amazing how useful I've found the extra storage. The advantage to this is that the space can be used, rather than almost solely decorative, as having the shelves open to the shower spray would be (PS, Sherman is adorable!)
I think it will work. I painted my small bedroom a similar color - Valspar's Urban Pulse - and it really makes it feel cozy. Your space will feel more intimate.

I think you need to change the kick plate to black. looks copper in the photo.  I would put a black planter in front of each of the columns and add a larger more colorful mat on the porch before painting the trim black.  I do like the black trim but agree with pennydesign and think that the yellow door gets a little lost
The "walk-in closet" isn't usable, since the space left between clothes is 2'-6" if it's actually built to the dimensions shown.
Wood tile looks best when the grout matches the tile.
In the campaign it's actually quite cool! And I kinda like the shark floor, could be fun in a public space like a pub.
Oh what a beautiful brick home you have!
That product has ruined your floors. You need to sand them down and start over.

You need to rearrange  everything as was suggested by shead above. That just isn't a good layout. Hers is far better. You need less of the appliance display at Home Depot look. You need taller stacked cabinets to the ceiling and NOT that staggered look. You need less of a bulky awkward continent and more of a actual designed piece of furniture. You need a hood that integrates into the cabinets better, or that has more open space around it to give it the emphasis it demands.

For what its worth, we love our vinyl plank. We have dogs, cats, horses. Its so easy to clean...just mop it and its done. We have it downstairs and up. Next winter, we will be installing it in the library. Looks like wood without the worry. The product has improved so much! Its not the 1970s vinyl anymore lol
Good suggestion from Sabrina, those windows don’t even have a profile.
The roof looks fine.  I love your door color.  Add more color plants in front of the porch.
I would go to the wall for a more spacious look near the steps. The stone are attractive so no need to hide them.

I also think about deep complex dramatic color next to the tile as one of the options..which exactly-will depend on the overall vision for the house..but I can think of several that would look fabulous next to that tile.
I love the way the house looks in your rendering with the siding I think your Dad would be proud you cared enough to make it beautiful
I prefer the chaise to be on the back side/corner of the room, so it doesn't physically and visually cut off the entrance into a room.
Design combination of triangular roof with a curved space below is beautiful!

I still think the cabinets are too yellow (warm) for the gray (cool) tile, but it can be really hard to judge undertones from photos. Why did you ask what we thought of the backsplash? Did it feel to you that it looks a bit off?
I would do 4 things only and painting the brick isn't one of them
Just an additional comment about the new white ikea shaker door--Axstad is a white white, but it's also thermofoil like Grimslov. So for a lot of people that's still not going to work.
Sometimes just changing the smallest and less expensive things can have the biggest impact. The handrail is nice but lost. Make it standout maybe a coat of black paint.
That backsplash, what a gorgeous piece of art that it!
I don't think you have room for all those swinging doors.
Much ado about nothing, when a few dabs of white paint on a dot in a flower would work. Tile doesn't "fade". That was the original color/shade of pink.

Not sure if it will help but I have Tilbar Lancaster Bianca which looks similar to what you're getting with light gray (Rolling Fog to be specific) grout.  The gray looks a little darker and very pretty in person.  The tile you picked looks perfect, and don't worry if it is slightly off from cabinets, and counters it will all blend in.  My whole kitchen is whiter, but you can see how the tile doesn't match exactly my cabinets and the marble but it all looks good together.  Did you pick #4 from your first choices by chance?

Well, all the rugs from esale arrived and sadly all of them are going back.  I ordered the Aria, Spectrum, Solaris, Trellis, Outdoor Modern and Harvest.  None of them fit look of the room in person and none of them made the wife go "Oh i like that one...".
I strongly suggest you reconsider a raised bar; they are out of fashion. I turned down an opportunity to cut one down today.
I think an arc lamp with that ceiling fan will just look wrong. Choose one or the other, not both.

If you plan to keep the azaleas, choose a house color that will not clash with them when they are blooming.  I have seen that happen too many times when people don't pay attention to blending blooming plants with the house colors.
It looks great together! That's the color I was leaning towards, it's nice to see it how well it's working for you. Thanks again.

Not a pro but personally, I cannot imagine putting a sink in an island that narrow.  I ALWAYS get water behind my sink when cleaning up.  In my case, it's not a big deal because my back splash stops it from spilling over the other side but in this case, it'll easily splatter/spill to the floor.  A wider island would stop the flow of water as well but you don't have that here.
That looks like a foam filled ceiling, making it near impossible to move and/or install new wiring.
Yes, still too busy, but the color looks right.  But really only you can be the judge of that as monitors are all different.
I like your idea. We have a small mudroom that continues into the laundry (both small, separated by a door, which I never close). It makes sens to go from mudroom to the laundry
Wow.  It is hard to believe that is the exact same layout.  Great job.

Please take a moment.... it is very tempting when you don't care for a space to jump in and start changing things. I completely understand that. But take the advice of everyone here... Wait...wait to change the cabinet color, wait to change the counter, wait to change the floors. These things are more permanent and costly. You don't even know yet how you will live in this space.... based on the pictures, the layout really isn't great. If you go ahead and spend thousands on a new top you are now locked into that layout before you even know if you like it. Not having a cabinet on the left of the stove is a bit dangerous.
We bought the French door refrigerator and have had no problems with it.
donna, those tiles in the bathroom pic are from Tilebar. I actually used those tiles for a client in a shower. they are very nice quality.

I'm a fire guy as well. However, in an island, I think it's going to depend on your venting. A surface-mount downdraft sucks a lot of the BTUs from a gas flame—that's what we had it in our last house. With proper overhead venting, that's not a concern.
that looks amazing!  I have always loved white cabinets, and I love your backsplash.
The only thing I’d touch in that picture is the lighting. And the unfortunate choice of a white oven when it needed to be stainless.

The quartz and granite composite sinks seem to be holding up quite well! Elkay and Blanco have some great lines, respectively. If you have a prep sink, one large basin for you main sink should suffice but it really depends on how you use your sink day-to-day. If you tend to use your kitchen sink for cleaning, you may want a second basin- 1 for drying dishes, 1 for rinsing rags, and the prep sink for food. If you plan on a dump sink in the laundry room to utilize for cleaning, consider allocating the space for you laundry room to be adjacent to the common areas so it is conveniently centralized for daily maintenance needs.  The recommendation would be to take notes on what you like and dislike about your sink situation now to help determine your ideals.

We purchased a Dacor and it has been the biggest lemon ever.  We've had it now for about 10 years and the local appliance repair has been out about yearly.  I've been looking to replace it with either a Wolf or a Thermador, 30", but not sure which way to go.  The Dacor has to go!

We used Clarino with honey oak cabinets in a kitchen and powder room.  We love it!  Has anyone found tile that complements it for a back splash.  White tiles are too white.  The white in Clarino is a warmer white.  Any ideas are welcome.

Got your point.  In the original plan, I had it where the family room was with a large wall opening between the living room and the dining. But, that had a 14' x14' size and we dont really use dining room at all.  Switching the positions gave me more space for the family room, freed a lot of space in the kitchen (it was cluttered before).  Plus, now I have a lot of shelf and desk space in the dining room and the room is more useful.
Black trim around the door for SURE! Try SW Chinese Red. Glorious pop of color with some personality.
Agree with what has already been suggested. I would also remove the dividers from the garage door windows.

If you paint it white, and still keep the cream trim, to me, it would look like you started to paint and never finished.  No, I would not do that.  I would just change the wall color in that room, which is a whole lot easier to do, than paint those cabinets.

Is the console with the TV centered directly across from the fireplace? If not, I would move it further to the left to center it.  The furniture is not centered on the fireplace currently and would look better if it was. The coffee table should be moved closer to the chairs and the sofa pulled further onto the rug. The common elements in the inspiration photos seem to be an injection of color and some drapes.

Everyone is right saying no to shutters.  Custom window box under double front window [and trimmed shrub as you've said] would be good.  With light [cream or white] window trim, be sure to accent the window Sashes with a dark contrast color - can be same as front door but can also be a fourth color.  Have balustrade top rail be the same as window sash color, and balusters be the light trim color.
I don't mind the shutters, but it might look better without them. Try it and see which you like more.
I love my thermadore range and yeah, the oven fan stays on for a while and is a tad aggressive but I have never found it to be overly problematic.

With Version 2, I would hate to have to walk through the mudroom where all the mud and wet is to get to the laundry area - it's convenient for when you come in from outside and are dirty but what about the other times you need to do laundry??
I think the larger size would  look best due to the size of the room and you have the space to do it.
One cannot go wrong with a dark marble or even slate for a fireplace surround.  Stay away from faddy.

Shallow cabinets above the fridge are pretty useless in my experience.  If you don't want deep ones, why put any cabinets there at ?  It is your kitchen, there is no rule you need cabinets above the fridge.
the white shelf is totally odd man out here.  either paint that a deep burgundy to go w/the rug and wall color, or find a wood shelf.
1. White cabinets will always be popular. There are different shades of white, but white should go with the current countertops.

Agree.  White walls; pretty shower curtain a la Marimekko or Dwell Studio.  I might also suggest you find a vintage Danish modern credenza to convert to a vanity, and find some cool retro bath lighting to finish it off.  The tile is great; don't touch it.
putting that door on your house as it is currently would not look the best.
Oh yes, obviously the heating unit is going to be changed out! And someone I know wants that wacky vintage faucet! Still works like a charm, I might add!

They look alright there, I would not have hung those blinds[horizontal] over a slider, as others have mentioned verticals work better, many choices out there that don't even resemble the verticals of the 70s and 80s. I think that you should consider them
the dangling light fixture needs to go.

It is not a super thick rug- but love the way it lays on my wood floor-nice and flat no problems with edges or corners.  I do agree with pink_ peony about the durability of the rug in your space.  My children are grown and my husband and I generally eat at  the breakfast bar, so the rug does not get much traffic. I considered this when I purchased this rug.  Also, I vacuum with the beater/roller off. I have 100% wool in my living room that gets frequent foot traffic.

NO better side.  In my guest room, the original holder was on the left, on the wall.  That is, until I slipped and fell, and hit it with my head, and knocked it completely out of the wall. :-)  To avoid trying to relocate it on the same wall (since I did a mesh patch in the drywall) I simply moved it to the right, on the side of the vanity.  No difference at all, really.

Since you have received so many responses, I haven't read through them all but my two cents worth says Ikea cabinets are fine for the money.  They may not last a lifetime but, then again, you may move and you've gotten your use from them.  Ikea cabinets are also great for rentals, as some renters are not as gentle with other's property as they would be with their own items.  Hope this helps! -- Laura
The furniture is gorgeous - it would be a shame to paint it and it looks wonderful with your bedding and your room.

We bought the Bracci Clarissa sofa a few months ago and absolutely love it. The leather is the best grade we've owned, far better than on a $9,000 Smith Brothers(American company)sofa we bought a few years ago. It if extremely comfortable and seats 5-6 adults quite comfortably. Our Clarissa is only a few months old, but we are 100% pleased with our purchase and would not hesitate to buy this brand again.
It just doesn't work to build a study area into a window for the reasons mentioned above, not to mention possible breakage of the window. We are talking about children, you know.
We remodeled out kitchen a year ago, and drawers were used to place all our pots and pans and plates and bowls.  Love it.  Easier on the back too!

Thanks Joyce, your kitchen looks wonderful!  The can lights were plugged in by the sales rep,  I would never put can lights in my old house.   We haven't even begun discussing lighting yet and since we're not hiring an electrician, whatever lighting we do will be pretty limited.  My kitchen is so bad right now that anything is an improvement so lighting is the least of my concerns.  I'm fine with an over the sink light and the ceiling fan.  I'm not too fussy.

I like it lengthwise also -  just leave a gap in front of the door for the vent. I like the colors in your rug with your artwork. I wouldn't add any furniture to the area near the door - maybe just on your staircase wall.
The bold printed tile is stunning! The mix of finishes is well allocated having created a rich balance in your space.

You have done a great job with the colors around the banquette.  I would probably replace the mosaic tile with a lighter look, perhaps marble or a glass (in a pale blue similar to the wall, or white). Glass tile reflects light and is a great contemporary look.   The darker tan paint  is sharp, but adds to the dark feeling on that side, maybe repaint somewhat paler?  If changing the tile isn't enough.
I live in coastal southern california too.  I would definitely cut the heated bathroom floors. I would also cut the free standing tub.  We have Kahrs engineered hardwood and have been very pleased.
I think concrete gray is a bit too cold a color for your cabinets..Might be a bit too dark too.
Another vote for keeping the wall. Your house looks great.
I like the chairs.  the artwork,,meh.   be better to find something w/the aqua/blues that go w/the chairs.

I would not like to walk in to a room that has windows on all sides with different /multi coloured fabrics hanging down ... A little bit of consistency but not necessarily 'the uniform ' is pleasant and soothing.
Oh, jalarse, I love your brick! It looks wonderful. Not sure why I like yours so much better than mine. :)
We love the look of white tile, but I'd have to agree with the light gray grout. The tile itself isn't hard to keep clean, it's the grout lines that get yucky and need the elbow grease.

I'd remove the too-small shutters, the wreath, and the tree that's going to end up too big. Replace it with a specimen plant that won't obscure the windows. Widen the steps and walkway, put a planter on the corner. Put a bench against the wall facing the garden. (I'd have included the bench but I couldn't find one that was facing the right way.)

Oh, what a beautiful room!  It has a very ethereal look about it.  I actually really like the gauzy-like curtains you currently have hanging.  And I agree that an Oriental rug in this space would be wonderful - perhaps in soft peach, cream, and green tones.
Right now the kitchen feels a bit too enclosed and there is not enough light flowing into it.

Hi, I finally decided to go with the thermador and I love it. I haven't used the oven a lot, but the cooktop is amazing... its powerful and at 18,000 BTUs for each burner, it gets the job done very fast. With the thermador range, I did get a free Thermador dishwasher, which was nice.
The corner with sink, fridge and corner of island looks a little tight.
Love the house.  Are the shutters black?  If so, your brick with black and white is classic.  The landscaping suggestions from Beverly and apple_pie are nice.
You're doing great, and even finding hidden storage! Loving the foyer!

I like the round one you suggested. The circular shape is good with your angular furniture, and I like the openness and color. I don't know if these are the right size, but I think the styles would work well for you - anything open and rounded.
I think the chandelier is hands-down the best element in the room.  It just makes the space, IMO.

IMO that fixture with cararra marble does not work plus the fact the bulbs look like edsisons which are horrible lighting almost everywhere and the mirror does nothing for the vanity in ORB or the rest in that finish
Love those chairs! Love them with your table, a beautiful set.

absolutely gas fireplace.  We have two, one in the living room and one in the master bedroom.  The gas fireplaces are a great supplement to our heat bills during the cold weather. No mess and no issues with anyone with respiratory issues.
For some reason , I ruled out fiberglass windows. It gets very hot in summer.
You'll never be able to clean around it, especially in the way back which will be out of arm's reach. It has reduced standing space compared to a regular built in tub.

I agree with mama goose - you have a very good layout right now. My kitchen is similar in layout, and when I am cooking I really appreciate that my appliances are reasonably close to each other but there is also a good amount of prep space. Since my kitchen is not too spread out, clean up is also easy and quick. I also totally agree with changing out the over the range microwave for a pretty hood. If you want to move the sink to the island, that is an option, but it means crossing aisles from sink to range - something I personally like to avoid.
It would work better attached to the perimeter as a peninsula than as an island.
Looking at the design of the entire house- a big window in the middle will be looking right out at a post for the front porch.
love your cabinet colors! your kitchen is looking great!

The biggest problem I see are the two contrasting colors of the wood ceiling and floors in Jen D’s house.  It would be a shame to remove those beautiful floors to match the ceiling.  But if painting the ceiling is out of the question it may be a consideration to replace the entire floor including using the same in the kitchen?
That's an a glorious amount of kitchen counter and storage space for an apartment, how wonderful!
It is narrow and everything looks too short for the niche.
I really like the way a rug 'grounds' a dining table. The lighting fixture is a little large IMO so I think adding the rug will create more balance.

Keep the mirrors and change the lighting but honestly clean out the room and then post pictures and some info as to what you are planning on doing besides ripping out the mirrors. IMO the mirrors are the least of your problems.
Those are actually nice light fixtures and I agree, would step up the space a little bit. Thanks!
Your floors are beautiful. Following trends is dangerous, the 1980's said bleached floors were the way, the 1990's said walnut, the early 2000's everyone was doing ebony...

Glass cabinets near a range, are a PAIN. Having a nice vent atop the range, that is WIDER,  than the rangetop is a great idea. Consider placing a wider range hood in that area.  ...  There is nothing on the edge of a cooktop that will not require alot more upkeep and cleaning maintenance, no matter which direction you look...
The mirror & the sink make it look “dated” to me.

That chevron tile only competes with the sink and IMO you want something that features the sink.  Consider running the mirror down behind the sink so nothing takes away from the sink and then place the chevron tile to the right and left
I think the floors are a big problem here. There needs to be contrast. Lighten up the floors & the countertop.
Um LOVE your kitchen. The backsplash you chose is perfect. And agree that the black hood is gonna make everything pop and look stunning!

Your couch and chair are beautiful. Since you said you don't have an eye for it, please notice the center cushion is placed backwards....turn the zipper to the back :-)  love some of the rug suggestions.
I actually like the window bare!  Such a beautiful view.  Why put something in front of it.
Looks like an awesome kitchen design! I love your color combo with the black white and wood detail. I agree that the backsplash should be more simple.

I actually dislike the floor more than the cabinets and I think if you went with a white quartz counter the contrast would be less but I honestly would live with the kitchen as is for a while to assess function before spending any money.
IMO vertical blinds are very dated but without seeing the actual space and window I wouldn’t know the answer to you question.
Room is lovely but you are missing lamps.......I would use lamps on end tables and a floor lamp by the chairs.
I don't like either with the honey oak.  If it were me, I'd put up a wall to separate the two areas!
Simple, solid backsplash with the veining in the countertops.  You don't want pattern in both.
I like the shutters on your house. They don't look too small for your windows. I would keep them.

Well I guess you're going to want to add some simple blue accents in the sitting room to coordinate with the kitchen. I'm not crazy about the red rug, but to be honest, there's no where I'd like to see it.

I am going to see it in person tomorrow and am so excited about this fridge (or as excited as I can get about a fridge).  I think gold/bronze tone hardware is coming into style and i'm not a fan of how it looks with stainless. That leaves one with very few non-dated looking options.
I hope you have separate HVAC for bedrooms 2 and 4 upstairs. That whole upstairs seems dark and claustrophobic.

You probably chose the wrong wood for your floor as white oak does turn an amber color although at a medium rate. A lot of time the stains look good at first and then turn an odd color as the wood does change color.

I love black walls and would paint a sunroom black without hesitation.  IMO black creates a fabulous backdrop for anything dramatic.  It makes colors pop and it highlights textures.  I don't think the above sunroom would be nearly as spectacular painted white or a light color.
Love that the dark color extends from the fireplace to the adjacent wall... and noticed the barn doors!
i myself would not paint the door black.. I would leave it as is
I used a white roller shade with white sheer on each side of the window. Pull shade when privacy needed.
I would pick a color that matches the drapes. No green, as that is to different from the rug.
We've had MSI quartz for 4 and 1/2 months now and have no stains at all; I do wipe up any spills as they occur. I don't use wine except very rarely for cooking so can't comment on wine stains.
DO NOT install "Bamboo" flooring if u live in a climate that has variable humidity factors. Our floors are shrinking and separatingpurchase.
I would look for a warmer grey. Consider a pattern such as chevron or a regular subway tile installed vertically.
It is for me. If I don't like the way I feel someone is pricing something, I'll go elsewhere rather than arguing.
Amazing bathroom transformation! The new bathroom looks very modern and elegant.
Beautiful space!

I can't help but wish you had chosen white bookshelves instead of black.  In conjunction with the gray-everything-else decor it seems to suck the light out of the room.  I would suggest large pottery vases and bowls for a more organic and personal look.  Large pieces of colorful art in this room would also be very nice.
I would keep the appliances consistent throughout the kitchen.
I would really consider skipping the rug on top of carpet, and adding your extra colors through interesting artwork, lamp,  and pillows instead.

kikodog, I LOVE the polished granite you chose, the honed would not have looked the same. I was looking at it for off white cabinets for my parents. Your kitchen is absolutely beautiful with the polished version and I personally prefer your white kitchen more than most I see lately....and I think it would be gorgeous with that tile from the photo (and the tulips and that LIGHT!!! ;))
UNBELIEVABLE!!  NO wonder you are pleased!!  Your bathroom is absolutely gorgeous!!!  What a transformation!  An inspiration to us all!!
I would trim the bushes in half. I usually vote for painting the brick, but yours looks good!

Forget marble entirely if you are searching for a “hard marble” that won’t  behave like marble. It doesn’t exist. You’re barking up entirely the wrong tree. You need to be looking at quartz if you want something with unnatural properties. Or laminate.
It looks like a walkway, so just find some nice artwork that you like. Maybe two large squares mounted vertically.
Revere Pewter will be a bit too dark for our walls since its a smaller darker kitchen. I may try to go  up one on the color chart and give that a try.
We don't like white cabinets. If money was no object, I would put in clear stain shaker cherry cabinets. The 16" cabinet is going to the right side of the kitchen by the toaster.
The new rug looks great and the chair looks fine with it. No reason to get a newer one. I don't see much gold/yellow in your rug but it might be a nice accent color to pick up for the throw.
I really like the idea of matching the garage door to the brick and putting the siding a lighter version.  What a great idea!

Hi char, I like the sideboard there, with the chairs straight, looks good.  The sideboard to me just seems to complete the room, I like your plants on the sideboard adds a bit of softness and ties in with the bigger plant in the corner.  My you are patient trying all these arrangements, good for you!
I think the gold vases might be too much. I'd go more for white vases or white and blue. Add texture with a floral. 2 or 3 vases and maybe a stack of books.

The cabinets are too nice to paint!  I like what you have now. I would change the pendants and the pulls, maybe you dont need pendants even. Simpler and bolder pulls would be good. I love the orange of your mixer. I am just decided to buy one in yellow!
The couches would be better in a fabric instead of leather and a distressed wood coffee table instead of glass. It's a great space!
I normally would agree with others here that matching the grout color to the tile is the best way to go, but white subway is a bit of an exception as it does look good with a darker grout.
It would probably work (there's blue in the rug) but I'm not a fan of blue in general.
I would have never bought this stove!
I would keep island white and I like the floor. Pretty kitchen.
Personally, I would do anything other than have a ceiling below 8 feet. Whether that means one lowered area for the beam or a post or whatever.

You have great windows and great views, the scarf behemoths make your living room look dated, heavy and old fashioned.   I would take them down in a heartbeat and loose the two wicker chairs and the floral one... open that room up.     Also table on patio, turn to an angle to open the view and take away two seats.         The furnishings/look now limit your buyer to 65 plus.
Clearly the black is more dramatic during the day, but at night, even with the lights on, it may not be as pretty.
Color, color, and more color. I feel like I'm looking at black and white photos :)
For the walls I would go with the lighter gray in the tiles.  A little darker on the vanity.
Its too many doors and a lot of wasted space.
Oh!  I am so in love with that room. I see a beautiful covered porch or patio through one of the side doors.  It just keeps getting better.
You might want to put a new counter top on just the island, it screams dated and is front and center.        You could change shape by adding overhang and add some seating..
I'm sorry I don't have an opinion on backsplash tile. Just wanted to say your counter tops are beautiful!!!

If you insist on losing that  pantry for that much refrigeration, the island needs to attach as a peninsula to the sink side to open up the traffic paths to them. Otherwise, it’s just a hip banger to have to constantly walk around.
Sorry to have to say...but this is hardly a "lake house".  It's very poorly designed, or hardly designed at all; simply an assemblage of rooms ganged together and a terrible exterior.
White or stainless would brighten up your kitchen. I would also replace the cabinet hardware at the same time.
Acknowledging that the granite is a natural element, does not make it more attractive or more complementary to the rest of the kitchen.
I am not seeing double doors , IMO the shutters take away from the house the siding color does not work with the brick and a new front door with some glass would be nice
I remodeled a kitchen a few years ago and used a mirror as the back splash.  The customer loved it as reflected a lot of light onto the cooking surface and was very easy to clean.
I think the crib looks nice centered on wall with wood behind it. Thank u!!

I think the color is a bit too green on the walls and a bit too dark.  Look for a nice lighter aqua, with no muddy tones.  That should brighten it up a bit.  Countertops, look to be in decent shape.  I would keep them for now, and just clean everything until it is sparkling.  Oh, and dont forget to remove the border.  Is that paper on the walls too?  Wonder if it is there to cover up something, if it is.
I would replace both counters and sinks.  The sinks do not match so even if you do (sort of) match the brown counter they will not look like they go together.
If me, I would put single drawers of 18”-21” in the center and the sinks on the end. As you have it right now, you both will be on top of one another.
Above navy accent chair looks very comfy & is dark in colour which makes it very practical.
I think your home is lovely.  My suggestion would be to lower the artwork over your fireplace.
I love the idea of an arc lamp in this space.  You have a great eye, the space looks wonderful, an arc lamp will be the cherry on top.
The star feature of the house is the bow window.
Your kitchen is beautiful and the color scheme I am going for in my bathroom.

Every type of granite stains the same, regardless the color. The best way to avoid any consequent staining of your countertop is to remove liquids or sauces from the countertop. If the liquid has already set, use a hot wet cotton cloth and dry off the surface at the end of this routine. Make sure to seal your granite each year. More on properly maintaining your granite you can read here. Snowfall granite will go beautifully with your white cabinets.
That counter looks very nice.  I know that Formica and all laminates have come a LONG way from what we remember in our parents' and grandparents' kitchens.

I like it too, Nora!  I am into grey woods and shiny metals a lot lately too.  I just decided that shiny metallic stuff (like your candlesticks and vases on the shelf) is what I want to do with the things on my fp wall at my lake house, and I just bought some blinds that look a lot like the wood on the circle side table you found. :)  Your coffee table is gorgeous.  The circle cutouts on the corners are begging for a circle side table, so I think you have the right one!
I’m not a pro, but as a busy cook, I prefer to not have the sink and DW between the fridge and stove.  So I‘d probably try to move the sink and DW to the right of the stove.

There is much one can do. Its as much a matter of  money. ;-) The least impact to the house itself would be to bring the grade up in several terraces using stacking concrete retaining wall block. Try not to have any one wall more than a couple feet high and let the wall layout be free-form. Add interest to the front by pushing out an entry with a gabled end and a covered porch. No need to gut just to reverse the floor plan. provide a space or two in the front for guest parking. I would make each terrace smaller than the one below. The terrace walls could blend into a single high wall on the garage side of the house. With such a home like this often dining/kitchen is pushed/added on at back to create a modern kitchen and to enlarge the living room. If you are finishing out the basement. then two small bedrooms on the main floor can be combine to create a master bedroom suite. New bedrooms below. Windows can be cut in on the exposed foundation. could be a fun project.

Your new plan is what I suggested, but I didn't realize that was a door/window next to the fireplace. Move the chair by the fireplace right next to the other chair. Then you should have room for the TV on the wall, as well as room to walk into the seating area and around the back of it.

The structure there looks deck-like (meant for the rear of the house) rather than front-porch-like. The wood railings have a barrier feel.

Based on the shape and layout of your house, there is a high likeliness that the wall between your kitchen and dining is holding up your second floor. That doesn't make opening up the two impossible, but do plan that you will likely need a (visible) beam along that line and depending on the bearing capacity of your outside and living room walls may need columns/wing walls at the ends of these new openings. An analysis of the existing framing needs to come sooner than later if it hasn't already been done.
